class="type-defaults"><p>Washington State Legislation RCW 19.27A.160 <a
href="../blog/2015-seattle-energy-code-lets-adapt.html#section2">[2]</a> mandates a 70% net reduction in energy consumed by new commercial buildings compared to the 2006 baseline. Per this legislation, “the council shall adopt energy codes from 2013 through 2031 that incrementally move towards achieving this reduction.” The recent energy code might affect design, building features, and increase costs for some, but in the long run, it’s one step further in reaching the 70% reduction mandate.</p><h2 class="redactor-heading-four"><strong>What are the most significant changes?</strong></h2><p>The response to this varies depending on who you ask, but in my experience over the last two years, the following three changes had the most impact on projects I have been associated with:</p><ol><li>Higher restrictions on the amount of vision glass architects can incorporate into a building design. Under a prescriptive approach, they are limited to a vision glass ratio of 40% or less.</li><li>Energy models are compared against high efficiency Dedicated Outdoor Air Mechanical Systems [DOAS] if Total Building Path energy code compliance is taken.</li><li>Enforced requirements for <a
href="http://www.seattle.gov/DPD/Publications/CAM/cam314.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">substantial alterations</a> [2015 SEC Chapter 5] of existing buildings and the implications it has on meeting the 2015 SEC. This is a significant change that affects owners wishing to expand or renovate a building.<br
/></li></ol><h2 class="redactor-heading-four"><strong>Which path will you choose?</strong></h2><p>Project owners can choose one of three routes to comply with the new code. This is another piece of the puzzle to consider that can be daunting—especially because it’s one of the first decisions to make.</p><ol><li>Prescriptive Pathway. The building is designed to the code minimum requirements in <a
href="http://www.seattle.gov/documents/Departments/SDCI/Codes/SeattleEnergyCode/2015SECCommercialChapter4.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Chapter 4 of the 2015 SEC</a> [except for 401.3 and 407].</li><li>Total Building Performance [TBP]. The proposed building is compared to the energy model of a reference building and needs to be between 7–13% more efficient than the reference model depending on the amount of C406 measures taken.</li><li>C401.3.2. The owner measures and verifies energy consumption for three years to confirm that it meets its target. If it doesn’t, the owner is fined on a sliding scale up to $4 per square foot. Up to 50% of the fine can be reinvested into the building for energy efficient measures.</li></ol><h2 class="redactor-heading-four"><strong>Implications</strong></h2><p><strong>Maintaining integrity of the design. </strong>Architects generally favor higher percentages of vision glass, which is understandable. The maximum ratio of vision to opaque wall is 40% under the prescriptive compliance path, but this is not an easy feat when trying to create an award-winning and/or unique design. Because of this specific requirement, many owners and architects are choosing the TBP pathway for code compliance because it allows a higher percentage of vision glass.</p><p>For example, if the envelope is more than 45% vision glass, you can offset the penalty by increasing energy efficiency in other areas [e.g. installing solar panels, ground source heat pumps, lower U Values for envelope assemblies, higher efficiency mechanical systems, etc.]. However, these offsets generally come with a higher price tag compared to baseline systems. At the end of the day, architects and engineers need to find alternative ways to make their building design unique and meet the energy code.</p></div><div
